= Discussion

Interpret your results here: what do they mean, how do they compare with earlier
work @jones2019 @garcia2021, and to what extent do they answer the question you
posed in the introduction? Begin with the main finding, relate it back to your
aim, and then broaden out to its wider significance.

Where your results agree with the literature, say so and explain why; where they
disagree, offer a plausible account of the difference @mueller2018. Distinguish
carefully between what the data show and what you infer from them.

== Limitations

State the limitations of your study honestly. Consider the data, the method, and
the analysis in turn, and explain how each limitation might affect the
conclusions. Acknowledging limitations strengthens a thesis rather than weakening
it — it shows you understand the boundaries of your own work.

== Future work

Suggest concrete next steps that would address the limitations or extend the
findings. Keep the suggestions specific enough that another researcher could act
on them.

== Conclusion

Close with a short, self-contained summary: restate the problem, your principal
finding, and why it matters, in a few sentences. The conclusion should leave the
reader with a clear sense of what the thesis contributes.
